data.content:
## What happened

C# 14 introduces new implicit span conversions. When you write `array.Contains(num)`, overload resolution now prefers **`MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)`** over `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Expression trees **cannot represent span-based methods**, so this throws at runtime (or may fail to compile in some contexts).

## How to fix

Cast the array to `IEnumerable<T>` so the compiler selects the `Enumerable.Contains` overload:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

The same issue affects **`Reverse()`** on arrays (resolves to the in-place `Span` extension instead of `Enumerable.Reverse`). Fix the same way: `Enumerable.Reverse(arr)` or `arr.AsEnumerable().Reverse()`.
